hostnames](https://github.com/microsoftgraph/msgraph-sdk-java-core/blob/21b1d75b5f10496a6916a33a4ead8d8425075988/src/main/java/com/microsoft/graph/authentication/BaseAuthenticationProvider.java#L14) is hardcoded in the current Java SDK.
Meaning that customizing the client creation will not be enough to call the test endpoint as it doesn't belong to any of the hardcoded hostnames.

On Go SDK we can do that by adding the following:
```golang
NewAzureIdentityAuthenticationProviderWithScopesAndValidHosts(yourCrendential, yourScopes, []string{"microsoftgraphvalidation.ags.msidentity.com"})
```

Ref:
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/graph/api/driveitem-copy?view=graph-rest-1.0&tabs=http

This API of copy drive item using graph API version 2.3.2 was working fine and since morning without any code change we are facing an issue. It seems that even if we pass the parent reference, still it's copying into the same directory as the source file.

We are copying files from one folder to another folder with a new path and name using graph API and kotlin

```
microsoftGraphClient.drives(documentStorage.driveId).items([fileToCopy.id](http://filetocopy.id/))
.copy(it.newPath.getFilename(), parentReference)
.buildRequest()
.post()
```

The above code was working till 18th-April-2022 and not working since 19th-April-2022 morning. It is copying files in the same directory as the source file instead of copying them into the new location.

Upon some searching it seems that the excel files in Sharepoint are reachable through a similar method as any file in OneDrive, thus any questions you may have about uploading, downloading, or modifying the excel files in Sharepoint should be easily answered through the OneDrive API endpoint: 
https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/graph/api/resources/driveitem?view=graph-rest-1.0
Using a code block similar to this should be helpful in reaching the files you need: 
```Java
DriveItemCollectionPage children = graphClient.sites("<Site(Page) ID>")
.drives("<Drive ID>")
.root().children()
.buildRequest()
.get();
````
Alternatively you can also use the ListItemCollection endpoint to reach these files: 
```Java
ListItemCollectionPage items = graphClient.sites("Site(Page) ID")
.lists("<Folder ID>")
.items()
.buildRequest()
.get();
``` 
The Site-ID should be in the form of <Domain>, <ID>, <ID>, to find an example try this on graph explorer:
